{"title":"{{< i18n business_case >}}","markdown":{"headingText":"{{< i18n business_case >}}","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-business-case","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n## Subsea Benthic Analysis AI – Environmental Intelligence Pipeline {.unnumbered}\n\n---\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThis **Business Case** justifies the investment in an AI-based pipeline for\nautomated screening of subsea imagery, with the primary goal of **strengthening\necological understanding and environmental governance** in Petrobras Subsea\noperations.\n\nThe initiative responds to a critical scalability challenge: the exponential\ngrowth of AUV inspection data has outpaced the capacity for manual ecological\nanalysis, increasing the risk of delayed assessments, specialist overload, and\npotential loss of environmentally relevant information.\n\nBy introducing AI-assisted screening as an enabling technology, the project\ndelivers **environmental value first**, while also generating measurable\noperational and economic benefits.\n\n---\n\n## Strategic Problem Statement\n\n### Current Situation (As-Is)\n\n- AUV inspection campaigns generate **millions of images per field**\n- Ecological and environmental analysis relies heavily on **manual expert screening**\n- Increased data volume leads to:\n  - Longer analysis cycles\n  - Higher specialist workload\n  - Reduced scalability of environmental studies\n- Environmental confidence depends on human capacity, which does not scale linearly\n\nThis creates a structural risk for:\n\n- Environmental baseline studies\n- Monitoring and impact assessments\n- Support to licensing and regulatory processes\n\n---\n\n### Strategic Risk of Inaction\n\nIf no action is taken:\n\n- Ecologically relevant benthic data may be **delayed, overlooked, or underutilized**\n- Environmental assessments become bottlenecks in subsea operations\n- Specialist overload increases operational and human risk\n- Environmental intelligence remains fragmented and non-reusable\n\nThis risk directly impacts Petrobras’ ability to operate responsibly and\nsustainably in complex offshore environments.\n\n---\n\n## Business Opportunity\n\n### Opportunity Description\n\nThe proposed solution introduces **AI-based automated screening of subsea\nimagery**, acting as a **scaling mechanism for ecological intelligence**.\n\nThe system does **not replace experts**; it filters noise so that experts can\nfocus on ecologically relevant content with higher confidence and consistency.\n\n---\n\n### Strategic Alignment (SUB / Petrobras)\n\nThe initiative aligns with Petrobras Subsea strategic drivers:\n\n- **Environmental stewardship and ecological responsibility**\n- **Digitalization of subsea inspection and monitoring**\n- **Reduction of human exposure and specialist overload**\n- **Creation of reusable digital environmental assets**\n- **Long-term cost efficiency through scalability**\n\n---\n\n## Value Proposition\n\n### Primary Value — Ecological and Environmental\n\n- Improved identification of benthic-relevant imagery at scale\n- Higher confidence in environmental baseline studies\n- Reduced risk of missing ecologically relevant features\n- More consistent ecological interpretation across campaigns and fields\n\n---\n\n### Secondary Value — Operational and Economic\n\n- Reduction in manual screening effort (≥ 30%)\n- Shorter analysis cycles (≥ 25%)\n- Lower cost per inspection campaign\n- Better allocation of specialist time to high-value analysis\n\n---\n\n### Long-Term Strategic Value\n\n- Creation of a reusable environmental AI capability\n- Accumulation of curated, versioned ecological datasets\n- Foundation for future environmental intelligence initiatives\n- Progressive adoption of MLOps within SUB\n\n---\n\n## Investment Rationale\n\n### Why Now\n\n- Data volume growth is accelerating\n- Manual processes are reaching practical limits\n- AI/CV technologies are sufficiently mature for screening tasks\n- Delaying action increases ecological and operational risk\n\n---\n\n### Why an MVP Approach\n\n- Reduces upfront investment and risk\n- Allows early validation with real operational data\n- Enables iterative improvement with SME oversight\n- Preserves flexibility for future expansion\n\n---\n\n## Cost–Benefit Considerations (Qualitative)\n\n### Cost Elements\n\n- Data science and engineering effort\n- Compute and storage resources\n- SME validation and annotation effort\n- Governance, documentation, and maintenance\n\n---\n\n### Benefit Elements\n\n- Reduced specialist hours per campaign\n- Faster environmental assessments\n- Reuse of models and datasets across fields\n- Avoided cost of delayed or repeated analysis\n\n---\n\n### ROI Logic\n\nROI is driven not only by cost reduction, but by **risk avoidance and value\npreservation**, particularly:\n\n- Avoidance of ecological oversight\n- Avoidance of rework due to late detection\n- Preservation of environmental credibility\n\n---\n\n## Options Analysis\n\n| Option | Description | Assessment |\n|------|-------------|------------|\n| Do Nothing | Maintain manual screening | Not scalable, high risk |\n| Partial Automation | Rule-based or limited tools | Low robustness |\n| **AI-Based Screening (Proposed)** | Precision-first AI + SME validation | **Best balance of value and risk** |\n\n---\n\n## Risks and Mitigation (Business Perspective)\n\n| Risk | Impact | Mitigation |\n|----|-------|-----------|\n| Model underperformance | Reduced trust | Conservative precision-first strategy |\n| Annotation subjectivity | Inconsistent outputs | Guidelines + consensus |\n| Adoption resistance | Low usage | SME involvement from start |\n| Over-automation | Ecological risk | Human-in-the-loop governance |\n\n---\n\n## Success Indicators (Business-Level)\n\n- ≥ 30% reduction in manual screening effort\n- ≥ 25% reduction in analysis cycle time\n- ≥ 85–90% retention of true benthic data\n- Positive validation by NOAA / SUB environmental specialists\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation\n\nProceed with the proposed MVP for AI-based automated screening of subsea\nimagery, recognizing it as a **strategic environmental investment**, with\nautomation serving as an enabler for ecological excellence, not as an end in\nitself.\n\nApproval of this Business Case authorizes transition to detailed Planning and\ncontrolled Execution phases.\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":true,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":false,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":false,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-install":true,"latex-clean":true,"latex-min-runs":1,"latex-max-runs":10,"latex-makeindex":"makeindex","latex-makeindex-opts":[],"latex-tlmgr-opts":[],"latex-input-paths":[],"latex-output-dir":null,"link-external-icon":false,"link-external-newwindow":false,"self-contained-math":false,"format-resources":[],"notebook-links":true,"format-links":["html","pdf"]},"pandoc":{"standalone":true,"wrap":"none","default-image-extension":"png","to":"html","metadata-files":["../location/pt.yml"],"toc":true,"css":["../styles.css"],"html-math-method":"mathjax","embed-resources":true,"output-file":"business_case.html"},"language":{"toc-title-document":"Índice","toc-title-webs